year with a woman back home.

45:23.533 --> 45:28.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their time together and apart,
and his life and work covering
a continent as a Pulitzer

45:30.533 --> 45:33.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Prize-winning correspondent for
The New York Times, make up the
story told in "Love, Africa:

45:33.233 --> 45:36.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
A Memoir of Romance,
War, and Survival."

45:36.533 --> 45:38.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Gettleman joins me now.

45:38.100 --> 45:40.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Welcome to you.

45:40.133 --> 45:40.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN,
Author, "Love, Africa: A
Memoir of Romance, War,
and Survival": Thank

45:40.666 --> 45:42.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

45:42.766 --> 45:43.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is a place,
a region that you have looked
at for a long time in a certain

45:43.700 --> 45:45.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
voice, right, as journalist.

45:45.600 --> 45:49.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But now you're presenting
a different voice.

45:49.266 --> 45:51.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is this?

45:51.333 --> 45:54.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: Well, I feel
very conflicted about my work
sometimes in Africa, because,

45:54.400 --> 45:57.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as journalists, we
focus on conflict.

45:57.100 --> 45:58.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We focus on argument
and dispute.

45:58.766 --> 46:02.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is
the way we hear about
Africa most of the time.

46:02.333 --> 46:04.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: And this
is true for all journalists.

46:04.600 --> 46:09.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But my job as a journalist
in East Africa, I'm often
steeped in these conflicts.

46:11.033 --> 46:13.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that wasn't why I came to
East Africa in the first place.

46:13.600 --> 46:17.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I came on a safari as
a student and was blown
away by the warmth, by
the sense of connectedness

46:19.700 --> 46:23.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
between people, like, just
a different way of life.

46:23.600 --> 46:26.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so this book, to me,
is a bit of an escape.

46:26.333 --> 46:31.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, often, we get
frustrated with what's
happening in today's world.

46:32.766 --> 46:34.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We feel sort of the woes
of the world on our back.

46:34.800 --> 46:38.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I wanted to write a book
that celebrated something
that meant a lot to me.

46:38.566 --> 46:41.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: You were
drawn to this place.

46:41.633 --> 46:43.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It wasn't real obvious why.

46:43.666 --> 46:47.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: I think,
thinking more deeply about
what it was that really moved

46:47.900 --> 46:52.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me, it was experiencing a
part of the world that's very
different from how I grew up in

46:52.466 --> 46:57.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
suburban Chicago, how most
of us grew up, a lot poorer,
a lot less developed.

46:59.433 --> 47:02.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there was this spirit,
this sense of warmth and
openness among people.

47:05.266 --> 47:09.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even though I had so much more
than the people I was around,
I felt very little resentment.

47:09.466 --> 47:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I felt very little bitterness.

47:11.500 --> 47:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I felt welcome in a part of
the world that couldn't be
any more different from what I

47:16.633 --> 47:18.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
experienced.

47:18.733 --> 47:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There is a
kind of fraught situation of
writing about Africa always,

47:21.633 --> 47:23.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
right, how to
write about Africa.

47:23.933 --> 47:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have to deal with that, as
a journalist and in this case.

47:26.600 --> 47:30.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: And I was
trying to be honest about that
in this book, because there's

47:30.066 --> 47:32.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
many books written by
passing correspondents.

47:32.400 --> 47:36.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And the term in Africa
is mzungu, which means
white man, like gringo.

47:36.966 --> 47:41.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I cover these conflicts, I go
into a famine zone, I go into
a part of South Sudan where

47:41.200 --> 47:43.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people are killing each
other, and they're stuck.

47:43.533 --> 47:44.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Their houses have been burned.

47:44.900 --> 47:46.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have lost everything
they have owned.

47:46.633 --> 47:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have lost loved ones.

47:48.800 --> 47:53.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're sharing their misery
with me, and I am dutifully
recording it in my notebook,

47:53.500 --> 47:55.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and then transmitting
it to the world.

47:55.533 --> 47:59.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then I get on a plane and
take off, and go back to my
wife and kids and my comfortable

47:59.233 --> 48:00.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

48:00.700 --> 48:03.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's morally
problematic in some ways.

48:03.833 --> 48:05.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But that's my role.

48:05.400 --> 48:06.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We all have our roles.

48:06.900 --> 48:08.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The aid workers have their
roles in delivering aid.

48:08.600 --> 48:11.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The militaries have their
role in providing security.

48:11.366 --> 48:16.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as a journalist, my role
is to just try and gather as
much material, and open a window

48:17.500 --> 48:19.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to a different
part of the world.

48:19.566 --> 48:22.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, in this
book, there is the other part
of the love story, which is

48:22.433 --> 48:25.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
your wife, who you
now go home too.

48:25.566 --> 48:30.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you're open about the
problems of a marriage amid
the life you are leading.

48:32.100 --> 48:35.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She leaves behind a
life as a lawyer to
come and work with you.

48:35.833 --> 48:39.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: i think what
we struggled with is what a
lot of young people struggle

48:39.800 --> 48:41.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
with.

48:41.200 --> 48:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We were both really determined
to pursue our careers.

48:42.933 --> 48:45.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She was dead set on being a
criminal defense attorney.

48:45.733 --> 48:47.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I really wanted to
be a journalist.

48:47.866 --> 48:51.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We had to go where the jobs
took us, and we did a lot of
damage to our relationship.

48:51.933 --> 48:56.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we didn't respect and honor
what we suspected that we had,
which was a very special bond.

48:59.000 --> 49:02.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there were years that we
screwed it up, and we threw
away a lot of time together.

49:02.533 --> 49:06.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's not
giving away the ending to say
that it worked out, right?

49:06.266 --> 49:11.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: Yes, we
were lucky enough to finally
sort of see which way is up.

49:12.300 --> 49:13.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we have a wonderful
life in Kenya.

49:13.566 --> 49:14.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's a great place
to raise a family.

49:14.800 --> 49:16.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have two little boys
that were born there.

49:16.800 --> 49:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What do you want
to convey here that we either
miss as viewer or watchers

49:23.300 --> 49:26.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of the world, or that
America itself misses,
right, in its policy?

49:26.533 --> 49:28.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN:
Where do I begin?

49:28.133 --> 49:30.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
OK, a couple quick things.

49:30.733 --> 49:34.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One is, in a lot of these
really bad situations,
there is an undercurrent
of hope, and of dignity,

49:36.566 --> 49:38.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and of humanity, and community.

49:38.766 --> 49:42.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For instance, I covered the
Westgate Mall massacre, where
some terrorists came into

49:42.733 --> 49:46.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a crowded mall in Nairobi, and
gunned down dozens of people.

49:46.566 --> 49:51.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They didn't kill more people,
because there was a response by
neighborhood police officers,

49:53.533 --> 49:56.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who were much more lightly
armed than these terrorists
that had assault rifles.

49:56.266 --> 50:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And these guys went streaming
into this mall, under fire, with
these cheap pistols, fighting

50:02.133 --> 50:04.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
against these terrorists.

50:04.200 --> 50:06.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were taking shots, they
were getting hit, they were
getting wounded, and they kept

50:06.466 --> 50:08.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
going.

50:08.466 --> 50:11.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These guys came in as
basically volunteers,
and saved a lot of lives.

50:11.600 --> 50:16.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, even in this moment, that
was there was still an element
of humanity, and community,

50:17.766 --> 50:19.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and pulling together
at the right time.

50:19.866 --> 50:24.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have seen that in war
zones, and in battle zones,
and in famine situations.

50:24.500 --> 50:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The one other thing I think is,
a lot of the problems in Africa
are because of things that

50:31.333 --> 50:34.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
happened outside of
Africa, or because of
American policy especially.

50:34.000 --> 50:38.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I wrote a bit in
this book about the
mistakes that the American
government has made under

50:38.633 --> 50:40.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
different administrations.

50:40.066 --> 50:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It wasn't a Republican
problem or a Democrat problem.

50:42.700 --> 50:44.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It was kind of a
lack of interest.

50:44.966 --> 50:49.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the results were famine,
and chaos, and pirates.

50:49.233 --> 50:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But some of that was because of
specific decisions the American
government had made that were

50:55.466 --> 50:57.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
bad decisions and led to
a whole chain of events.

50:57.533 --> 51:00.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But in this part of the world,
a lot of people aren't paying
that close of attention.

51:00.833 --> 51:04.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I felt that it was my
responsibility to write a very
personal book, an accessible

51:04.966 --> 51:09.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
book, a kind of escape,
adventure story, but
to do some educating.

51:09.566 --> 51:13.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right,
the book is "Love, Africa."

51:13.033 --> 51:14.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Gettleman,
thank you very much.

51:14.033 --> 51:16.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: Thank you.

51:16.466 --> 51:20.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Read Jeffrey
Gettleman's reflections
on closing The New
York Times' East Africa

51:20.900 --> 51:22.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
bureau.

51:22.100 --> 51:25.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
His essay was published
by The Times today.

51:25.200 --> 51:30.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
